commit.message:
Skip broken tests on windows

Make CI green for windows as a starting point so we can defend existing
working tests.

Intent is to revert this patch and then include fixes.
Fix loose pack detection on windows
Canonicalize to unix paths in elfshaker_sha1sums

Ignore ./elfshaker_data while finding files

We had an existing mechanism to do this, but it does not work well on
windows+wine, because the paths become rather complicated.

Early during walk, reject */elfshaker_data. We should be the only users
of this name so it should have minimal impact.

Ideally this logic would just reject ./elfshaker_data and it should be
updated to that but I'm fine with this workaround for now while getting
windows test infra up and running.

Handle file permissions in a cross-platform way

By introducing FileMode, and a shim for Windows.

Do not compile atomicfile for Windows

It uses API which are not readily available, and since atomicfile is not
used, just disable building it for Windows.

Do not use hardcoded path separator

Windows uses \ instead of /.
Release: show more log lines on build failure
Make manyclangs-run work outside the ELFSHAKER directory

Remove _RUSTFLAGS

It looks like recent toolchains already do the right thing; I don't know
when the fix came in, but updating them seems to have resolved some
problems.
Enable x86 cross tests (use pic rather than pie)
Use $TMP for tmp space rather than /dev/shm

Implement 'nix build .#release' to build release tarballs

Some notes:

* `nix build .#release` creates a result symlink containing artefacts to
  be uploaded to github. At the moment, those are .tar.gz and .sha256sum
  files containing just an elfshaker binary.
* The toolchains we use for release are cargo 1.71.1 (7f1d04c00
  2023-07-29), rustc 1.71.1 (eb26296b5 2023-08-03),
  and C/C++ compilers and dependencies acquired from  nixos-unstable
  as of today.
  * nixos-unstable is used because that is the one the various cross
    compilers are available in the nix caches for. Additionally those
    cross compilers have had various fixes in recent times. Using a release
    branch unfortunately means requiring that users build the compilers
    which isn't ideal, so I would prefer to use (a pin of) the
    nixos-unstable branch to avoid building compilers.
* We build musl binaries to avoid a glibc version dependency and make a
  fully static binary.
* We can cross compile from Linux between architectures.
* We can cross compile from Linux to Windows.
* The same build also works on Darwin (not cross).
* Cross compile between architectures on Darwin doesn't work.
* Cross compiling to Darwin from Linux doesn't work.
* It looks as though cross compiling from Darwin to Linux (and windows)
  might be possible to make work. But since we can't cross between
  two Darwin architectures, we're forced to have more than one piece of
  build infrastructure; if we've got more than one we may as well have a
  linux specific builder.
* The aarch64->x86 Linux 'cargo test' is broken (noted next to 'doCheck' in
  elfshaker.nix) during the dep building phase. It succeeds when
  building elfshaker itself. Since the tests pass I'm not worried, the
  issue appears to have to do with building the test binary as PIE
  statically, I haven't investigated more deeply.

The windows build is currently broken due to parts of our implementation
being unavailable on windows. This needs fixing at some point.

You can drop into a development shell with the same toolchain used for
relese with 'nix develop' (or `echo use flake > .envrc && direnv allow`
to make it automatic when you enter the directory). This can also be
used to build cross binaries with `cargo build --release --target
<triple>`.

My current intent is to run this all in a github action when a release
is tagged, so that we get release binaries made through that route for
each of the architectures.

Bump version to 1.0.0-rc1 in preparation for release

Note that the version before this commit was incorrect, it was showing
0.1.0, but we released this on github as 0.9.0.
